to make a couple of stops...

275
00:13:55,453 --> 00:13:57,720
Alfie, I told you to
take him right to the Waldorf!

276
00:13:58,957 --> 00:14:00,677
Now I gotta slam your
brakes on, Mr. Silver.

277
00:14:00,758 --> 00:14:03,426
When I'm driving Mr. Swann,
he's chief of the car.

278
00:14:03,528 --> 00:14:05,506
And when the chief says he
wants to make some stops,

279
00:14:05,530 --> 00:14:07,997
Alfie Bumbacelli makes the stops.

280
00:14:08,099 --> 00:14:09,632
And that's what I live by.

281
00:14:09,734 --> 00:14:13,703
Well, at least we've got
plenty of time to replace him.

282
00:14:13,805 --> 00:14:14,537
Dump him!

283
00:14:14,639 --> 00:14:15,972
Leo.

284
00:14:16,074 --> 00:14:16,973
Isn't there some way?

285
00:14:17,075 --> 00:14:19,442
I mean, the man is a legend.

286
00:14:19,544 --> 00:14:20,576
Stan, what do you think?

287
00:14:24,282 --> 00:14:25,282
I don't know.

288
00:14:28,019 --> 00:14:30,052
He is a legend.

289
00:14:30,154 --> 00:14:31,754
One of the biggest stars ever.

290
00:14:31,856 --> 00:14:33,322
He's one of a kind.

291
00:14:33,424 --> 00:14:37,727
A guy like this is irreplaceable.

292
00:14:37,829 --> 00:14:39,762
Replace him, Leo.

293
00:14:39,864 --> 00:14:40,864
You can't!

294
00:14:40,898 --> 00:14:41,631
Too risky.

295
00:14:41,733 --> 00:14:42,531
He's out.

296
00:14:42,634 --> 00:14:43,634
King!

297
00:14:47,171 --> 00:14:48,738
You're right.

298
00:14:48,840 --> 00:14:50,006
This is too risky.

299
00:14:50,108 --> 00:14:53,376
You can't take a chance
with something like this.

300
00:14:53,478 --> 00:14:56,012
Look, King, you're a big star now,

301
00:14:56,114 --> 00:14:59,749
and I'm sure you always will be.

302
00:14:59,851 --> 00:15:02,918
But suppose... just
suppose, and I know

303
00:15:03,021 --> 00:15:05,621
this is never going to happen...

304
00:15:05,723 --> 00:15:08,724
But suppose someday
you wind up like this.

305
00:15:11,162 --> 00:15:13,829
I hope nobody does to you
what you're doing to him.

306
00:15:18,302 --> 00:15:19,368
Dump him.

307
00:15:25,009 --> 00:15:28,244
Who are you to talk to me
like that, you little Jiminy.

308
00:15:28,346 --> 00:15:29,679
Cricket pest bastard?

309
00:15:32,283 --> 00:15:33,749
All right, he gets one more chance.

310
00:15:33,851 --> 00:15:34,183
- No!
- Yes!

311
00:15:34,285 --> 00:15:36,952
Yes!

312
00:15:37,055 --> 00:15:40,222
But now you, you're going
to be responsible for him.

313
00:15:40,324 --> 00:15:42,525
Swann better be at every rehearsal sober,

314
00:15:42,627 --> 00:15:45,861
or it's your ass, you understand?

315
00:15:45,963 --> 00:15:46,862
Now, see, Sy?

316
00:15:46,964 --> 00:15:47,697
This kid's got balls.

317
00:15:47,799 --> 00:15:48,799
Oof!

318
00:15:51,803 --> 00:15:53,536
A week's salary Swann takes a dive.

319
00:15:53,638 --> 00:15:54,336
Hey!

320
00:15:54,439 --> 00:15:55,304
Swann dive!
Ba-dum-bum!

321
00:15:55,406 --> 00:15:56,406
You're on.

322
00:16:04,048 --> 00:16:07,049
Double the lad's bet for me, you toad.

323
00:16:12,757 --> 00:16:14,390
OK, now, pick a card, good, any card.

324
00:16:15,326 --> 00:16:16,225
Priscilla.

325
00:16:16,327 --> 00:16:17,760
Come here.

326
00:16:17,862 --> 00:16:20,429
And now put it back
in the deck, anywhere.

327
00:16:20,531 --> 00:16:21,697
How long you workin' here?

328
00:16:21,799 --> 00:16:22,364
Here.

329
00:16:22,467 --> 00:16:24,033
About a year.

330
00:16:24,135 --> 00:16:25,334
You look real nice today.

331
00:16:25,436 --> 00:16:26,502
Thank you.

332
00:16:26,604 --> 00:16:28,337
Here, write your address on here.

333
00:16:28,439 --> 00:16:29,439
Put it on my desk.

334
00:16:29,474 --> 00:16:31,373
I'm gonna send you some steaks.

335
00:16:31,476 --> 00:16:32,508
Is that your card?

336
00:16:32,610 --> 00:16:34,143
Yeah, that's my card!

337
00:16:34,245 --> 00:16:38,180
Mr. Silver, Boss Rojeck and
his lawyer are in your office.

338
00:16:38,282 --> 00:16:39,648
It's about the Boss Hijack sketch.

339
00:16:45,456 --> 00:16:46,956
Hey, where are you going?

340
00:16:47,058 --> 00:16:47,823
With you.

341
00:16:47,925 --> 00:16:48,524
What for?

342
00:16:48,626 --> 00:16:50,359
To meet Boss Rojeck.

343
00:16:50,461 --> 00:16:51,327
Stan.

344
00:16:51,429 --> 00:16:52,928
What's the matter with you?

345
00:16:53,030 --> 00:16:56,465
You think he's here because he
likes the Boss Hijack sketch?

346
00:16:56,567 --> 00:16:58,167
You think he likes being made a fool

347
00:16:58,269 --> 00:17:01,871
out of by you in front of 20
million people every week?

348
00:17:01,973 --> 00:17:03,072
I don't know.

349
00:17:03,174 --> 00:17:04,673
Stan.

350
00:17:04,776 --> 00:17:07,943
He's here because he wants us
to drop the Boss Hijack sketch.

351
00:17:08,045 --> 00:17:09,845
Think so?

352
00:17:09,947 --> 00:17:10,947
Let's go find out.

353
00:17:10,982 --> 00:17:12,281
All right, all right.

354
00:17:12,383 --> 00:17:13,883
Maybe you better change first.

355
00:17:13,985 --> 00:17:14,884
Why?

356
00:17:14,986 --> 00:17:16,886
Well, that outfit might set him off.

357
00:17:26,697 --> 00:17:29,098
Mr. Rojeck, sir,
I think you've made

358
00:17:29,200 --> 00:17:30,533
a wise decision to come here.

359
00:17:30,635 --> 00:17:32,715
I think these gentlemen
will be able to talk to us...

360
00:17:33,571 --> 00:17:35,171
about our problem in a mature way.

361
00:17:35,273 --> 00:17:37,306
I'm sure they'll see reason, sir,

362
00:17:37,408 --> 00:17:41,210
and there should be
no problem whatsoever.

363
00:17:41,312 --> 00:17:42,312
Myron Fein.

364
00:17:42,380 --> 00:17:45,281
I'm Leo Silver.

365
00:17:45,383 --> 00:17:46,448
This is King Kaiser.

366
00:17:46,551 --> 00:17:48,083
What do you say, Myron?

367
00:17:48,186 --> 00:17:49,218
My client, Karl Rojeck.

368
00:17:50,254 --> 00:17:51,254
Karl?

369
00:17:51,355 --> 00:17:52,355
It's not Boss?

370
00:17:52,390 --> 00:17:53,390
Stan!

371
00:17:55,426 --> 00:17:56,659
Gentlemen.

372
00:17:56,761 --> 00:17:58,241
We'll all be sitting
down, Mr. Rojeck.

373
00:18:05,102 --> 00:18:07,903
I'm sure we're all aware
that my client, Mr. Rojeck,

374
00:18:08,005 --> 00:18:11,440
is one of the most respected
labor leaders in America today.

375
00:18:11,542 --> 00:18:13,342
That's why they subpoenaed him.

376
00:18:13,444 --> 00:18:14,777
Stan!

377
00:18:14,879 --> 00:18:16,599
Mr. Kaiser, a subpoena
is not an indictment.

378
00:18:17,949 --> 00:18:19,982
Now, it has come to our
attention that on two

379
00:18:20,084 --> 00:18:21,116
separate occasions...

380
00:18:21,219 --> 00:18:25,054
September 4th, 1954, and
September 18th, 1954...

381
00:18:25,156 --> 00:18:27,723
A character referred to as
Boss Hijack was portrayed

382
00:18:27,825 --> 00:18:29,158
on your television program.

383
00:18:29,260 --> 00:18:31,627
We feel that this
character to a great degree

384
00:18:31,729 --> 00:18:33,929
is based upon my client.

385
00:18:34,031 --> 00:18:34,897
That's you, Karl.

386
00:18:34,999 --> 00:18:36,599
Well, according to our lawyers,

387
00:18:36,701 --> 00:18:40,636
your client is a public
figure and as such

388
00:18:40,738 --> 00:18:43,205
has already forfeited
certain rights of privacy.

389
00:18:43,307 --> 00:18:44,640
Granted.

390
00:18:44,742 --> 00:18:46,520
However, even though Mr.
Rojeck concedes that point,

391
00:18:46,544 --> 00:18:48,310
he feels that the
portrayal of said character

392
00:18:48,412 --> 00:18:51,747
is slanderous and defamatory
and done with malicious intent,

393
00:18:51,849 --> 00:18:54,016
therefore abrogating the
public figure defense

394
00:18:54,118 --> 00:18:55,118
and rendering it...

395
00:18:59,457 --> 00:19:01,023
to wit, actionable.

396
00:19:01,125 --> 00:19:02,524
Did you say that, Karl?

397
00:19:02,627 --> 00:19:05,361
What a guy.

398
00:19:05,463 --> 00:19:07,763
That's it.

399
00:19:07,865 --> 00:19:09,999
I want to clear some things up here.

400
00:19:11,135 --> 00:19:13,602
This is a stupid show.

401
00:19:13,704 --> 00:19:16,505
And that is a stupid, stupid suit.

402
00:19:16,607 --> 00:19:19,275
And I don't want to see it no more.

403
00:19:19,377 --> 00:19:22,244
Hey, take it easy, Karl.

404
00:19:22,346 --> 00:19:25,547
I mean, if you really don't
want to see it no more,

405
00:19:25,650 --> 00:19:26,815
then don't watch.

406
00:19:26,918 --> 00:19:27,816
Stan!

407
00:19:27,919 --> 00:19:29,785
Let me explain something to you, Karl.

408
00:19:29,887 --> 00:19:32,221
We're going to keep on doing the sketch.

409
00:19:32,323 --> 00:19:33,555
You know why?

410
00:19:33,658 --> 00:19:34,957
Because it's funny.

411
00:19:35,059 --> 00:19:39,094
And in my business, you never cut funny.

412
00:19:39,196 --> 00:19:40,462
Funny?

413
00:19:40,564 --> 00:19:43,866
Let me tell you about
the business I'm in.

414
00:19:43,968 --> 00:19:46,168
I'm in the removal business.

415
00:19:46,270 --> 00:19:49,905
Now, if I were to feel
that this stupid thing

416
00:19:50,007 --> 00:19:55,644
from this stupid show is
bothering me, I'd remove it.

417
00:19:58,416 --> 00:19:59,448
You see, it's gone.

418
00:20:00,618 --> 00:20:01,817
And I feel good.

419
00:20:01,919 --> 00:20:05,454
Now, that's how the
removal business works.

420
00:20:05,556 --> 00:20:06,722
Do I make myself clear?

421
00:20:06,824 --> 00:20:08,302
I think everyone
understands, Mr. Rojeck.

422
00:20:08,326 --> 00:20:09,191
Should we leave?

423
00:20:09,293 --> 00:20:10,526
No, no, wait, wait, wait.

424
00:20:10,628 --> 00:20:12,394
I'm not clear about a
couple of things here.

425
00:20:12,496 --> 00:20:15,397
What you're saying is that
in this removal business,

426
00:20:15,499 --> 00:20:23,499
if something bothers you...
Like, like say this...

427
00:20:24,408 --> 00:20:25,607
Then you remove it.

428
00:20:25,710 --> 00:20:29,578
- Stan, that is a cashmere coat.
- Like that!

429
00:20:29,680 --> 00:20:31,513
Stan!

430
00:20:32,950 --> 00:20:33,816
You know, you're right.

431
00:20:33,918 --> 00:20:35,351
You do feel better.

432
00:20:35,453 --> 00:20:37,553
I like the removal business.

433
00:20:37,655 --> 00:20:39,455
I want you.

434
00:20:39,557 --> 00:20:40,557
Come on.
Come and get me.

435
00:20:41,459 --> 00:20:43,192
Come on, come on.

436
00:21:01,278 --> 00:21:04,813
A fight is rounds.

437
00:21:04,915 --> 00:21:06,015
This is Round One.

438
00:21:21,132 --> 00:21:23,432
So the first time I drive him is, what?

439
00:21:23,534 --> 00:21:24,400
Right before the war.

440
00:21:24,502 --> 00:21:25,968
1938.

441
00:21:26,070 --> 00:21:27,970
That makes it 16 years.

442
00:21:28,072 --> 00:21:28,637
Yeah.

443
00:21:28,739 --> 00:21:30,339
We go way back.

444
00:21:30,441 --> 00:21:31,206
You drive anyone else?

445
00:21:31,308 --> 00:21:32,341
Sure.

446
00:21:32,443 --> 00:21:34,343
But when Mr. Swann's in
town, I drop everything.

447
00:21:41,385 --> 00:21:44,286
Upstairs, boys, all right?

448
00:21:47,925 --> 00:21:50,025
La, la, la, la, la, la!

449
00:21:57,435 --> 00:21:58,435
Oof!

450
00:22:02,673 --> 00:22:04,339
Wonderful to be alive.

451
00:22:15,686 --> 00:22:16,985
Make sure you don't fall.

452
00:22:22,359 --> 00:22:25,761
What is our estimated time of arrival?

453
00:22:33,571 --> 00:22:36,405
Go ahead and lash me, you swine!

454
00:22:36,507 --> 00:22:38,674
You'll not loosen my tongue.

455
00:22:38,776 --> 00:22:41,510
That's from "Captain From Tortuga"!

456
00:22:44,448 --> 00:22:47,015
Excuse me.

457
00:22:47,118 --> 00:22:48,838
Had this made special
for when he travels...

458
00:22:48,886 --> 00:22:49,952
Calls it his 'drunk suit.'

459
00:23:06,470 --> 00:23:11,240
I have to remind him to
work on some tear-away shoes.

460
00:23:11,342 --> 00:23:12,174
Good idea.

461
00:23:12,276 --> 00:23:17,312
My god, I'm blind.

462
00:23:17,414 --> 00:23:20,582
I cannot see.

463
00:23:20,684 --> 00:23:23,152
Help me get him into the tub.

464
00:23:23,254 --> 00:23:24,254
I got him.

465
00:23:37,201 --> 00:23:39,434
This is probably more than $35 a night?

466
00:23:39,537 --> 00:23:40,636
Tried Try $250.

467
00:23:40,738 --> 00:23:43,906
$250 a night?

468
00:23:44,008 --> 00:23:46,108
Well, what's that mean
to a guy like Alan Swann?

469
00:23:46,210 --> 00:23:48,377
Nothing... when
you ain't got nothing,

470
00:23:48,479 --> 00:23:49,511
it don't mean nothing.

471
00:23:49,613 --> 00:23:51,046
What are you talking about?

472
00:23:51,148 --> 00:23:54,316
You're looking at tap city in there.

473
00:23:54,418 --> 00:23:54,950
That's his stockpile.

474
00:23:55,052 --> 00:23:56,318
Grab 'em, will you?

475
00:23:59,056 --> 00:24:00,589
These must be his drinking socks.

476
00:24:03,961 --> 00:24:05,794
Who's this?

477
00:24:05,896 --> 00:24:07,329
That's Tess, his daughter.

478
00:24:07,431 --> 00:24:09,565
Daughter... I didn't
know he had a daughter.

479
00:24:09,667 --> 00:24:10,566
Where is she?

480
00:24:10,668 --> 00:24:12,768
She's in Connecticut.

481
00:24:12,870 --> 00:24:14,636
He always has one secret bottle hidden

482
00:24:14,738 --> 00:24:16,438
somewhere for emergencies.

483
00:24:24,048 --> 00:24:25,048
We got them all now.

484
00:24:33,290 --> 00:24:35,290
Nah, that guy never actually shot him.

485
00:24:35,392 --> 00:24:37,326
You see, they were
supposed to have this duel,

486
00:24:37,428 --> 00:24:39,394
and I think it was over that Peron dame.

487
00:24:39,496 --> 00:24:41,998
Anyhow, they both showed up drunk...
Alfredo!

489
00:24:42,066 --> 00:24:45,434
And Swan sort of shot himself.

490
00:24:56,614 --> 00:24:58,780
Alfredo, my dear old chum.

491
00:24:58,882 --> 00:25:00,722
Tell me, how in the name
of God did I get here?

492
00:25:00,818 --> 00:25:02,050
Begin at the airport.

493
00:25:02,152 --> 00:25:03,785
This is Benjy Stone, one of the writers

494
00:25:03,887 --> 00:25:04,653
from "Comedy Cavalcade."

495
00:25:04,755 --> 00:25:05,988
How do you do?

496
00:25:06,090 --> 00:25:07,801
Alfredo, we should pop
in and see these people.

497
00:25:07,825 --> 00:25:08,890
Yes.

498
00:25:08,993 --> 00:25:11,093
Plenty of time
tomorrow, Mr. Swann.

499
00:25:11,195 --> 00:25:13,562
And since this is your first
time working in television,

500
00:25:13,664 --> 00:25:14,975
they've asked me to stay with you

501
00:25:14,999 --> 00:25:16,932
and help you over some
of the rough spots.

502
00:25:17,034 --> 00:25:18,267
Like showing up?

503
00:25:18,369 --> 00:25:24,273
That's one, another is not passing out.

504
00:25:24,375 --> 00:25:26,141
An honest one.

505
00:25:26,243 --> 00:25:28,477
Signor Bumbacelli,
we'll be two for dinner.

506
00:25:28,579 --> 00:25:29,978
Telephone The Stork Club.

507
00:25:30,080 --> 00:25:31,880
You sure you mean
The Stork Club, Mr. Swann?

508
00:25:31,982 --> 00:25:33,015
Certainly.

509
00:25:33,117 --> 00:25:34,517
It's been a year and a half, surely

510
00:25:34,585 --> 00:25:37,386
they've repaired the wall
and the bandstand by now.

511
00:25:37,488 --> 00:25:40,088
Would you like to talk about
the sketch before you leave?

512
00:25:40,190 --> 00:25:41,190
On an empty stomach?

513
00:25:41,225 --> 00:25:43,158
No, we'll talk over dinner.

514
00:25:43,260 --> 00:25:47,129
Me, you The Stork Club?

515
00:25:47,231 --> 00:25:48,964
Well, after that rather eloquent speech

516
00:25:49,066 --> 00:25:50,944
you made earlier this
morning, I didn't think you'd

517
00:25:50,968 --> 00:25:52,501
mind having dinner with me.

518
00:25:52,603 --> 00:25:54,936
You heard that?

519
00:25:55,039 --> 00:25:56,071
But you were out.

520
00:25:56,173 --> 00:25:59,608
There's out and there's out.

521
00:25:59,710 --> 00:26:01,510
I'd like I'd like to reservation.

522
00:26:01,612 --> 00:26:06,715
Well, Stone, what sort
of heroic idiot am I this time?

523
00:26:06,817 --> 00:26:07,916
A musketeer idiot.

524
00:26:08,018 --> 00:26:10,085
I read that on the airplane...

525
00:26:10,187 --> 00:26:11,653
Very funny, very good.

526
00:26:11,755 --> 00:26:12,621
I wrote that.

527
00:26:12,723 --> 00:26:15,090
Did you?

528
00:26:15,192 --> 00:26:17,559
Bravo, Stone... bravo.

529
00:26:17,661 --> 00:26:20,696
OK, Mr. Swann, table
for two at The Stork Club.

530
00:26:20,798 --> 00:26:21,798
Let's move it.

531
00:26:21,865 --> 00:26:24,066
Comedy is such a mystery to me.

532
00:26:24,168 --> 00:26:25,934
I feel the way Edmund Kean did.

533
00:26:26,036 --> 00:26:27,669
The great English actor?

534
00:26:30,107 --> 00:26:33,575
On his deathbed, Kean
was asked how he felt.

535
00:26:33,677 --> 00:26:41,016
He answered, dying is
easy, comedy is hard.

536
00:27:05,909 --> 00:27:07,175
Thanks, Mr. Charles.

537
00:27:07,277 --> 00:27:10,979
Mr. Swann... A pleasure to see you, sir.

539
00:27:11,081 --> 00:27:13,215
Pleasure to be seen.

540
00:27:13,317 --> 00:27:16,118
Benjamin Stone, my colleague.

541
00:27:16,220 --> 00:27:18,920
Alan, you're looking
absolutely marvelous.

542
00:27:19,022 --> 00:27:20,522
- As do you.
- Proper jacket.

